  <exercise xml:id="ez-8a-1-1">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Throughout our work in <xref ref="sec-8a-1-linear-poly">Section</xref>, we have focused on approximating the function <m>f(x) = e^x</m>.  In this exercise, we change the function of interest to <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + \frac{1}{4}x^2 - 2x - 1</m>, and consider the linear and quadratic approximations to <m>f</m> near <m>a = 0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        <ol  marker="a.">
          <li>
            <p>
              Determine <m>f'(x)</m> and <m>f''(x)</m> and enter their formulas in rows 2 and 3 of <xref ref="T-ez-8a-1-1">Table</xref>.
            </p>

          <table xml:id="T-ez-8a-1-1">
            <title>Formulas and values for <m>f(x)</m>.</title>
              <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor">
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\frac{1}{3}x^3 + \frac{1}{4}x^2 - 2x - 1</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Next, compute <m>f(0)</m>, <m>f'(0)</m>, and <m>f''(0)</m> and enter those values in rows 4-6 in <xref ref="T-ez-8a-1-1">Table</xref>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use your work so far to determine the formula for <m>L(x)</m>, the tangent line approximation to <m>f(x)</m> at <m>a =0</m> (which satisfies <m>L(0) = f(0)</m> and <m>L'(0) = f'(0)</m>).
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>Q(x)</m> be the quadratic approximation to <m>f(x)</m> near <m>a = 0</m> that satisfies <m>Q(0) = f(0)</m>, <m>Q'(0) = f'(0)</m>, and <m>Q''(0) = f''(0)</m>.  You might start by letting <m>Q(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m>, and creating an updated table like the one shown in <xref ref="T-ez-8a-1-1-updated">Table</xref>.
            </p>
          <table xml:id="T-ez-8a-1-1-updated">
            <title>Formulas and values for <m>f(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)</m>.</title>
              <tabular top="minor" bottom="minor">
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>\frac{1}{3}x^3 + \frac{1}{4}x^2 - 2x - 1</m></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>Q(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>Q'(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><m>c_1 + 2 c_2 x</m></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>Q''(x)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin /></cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                  <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>Q(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>Q'(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                </row>                
                <row>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>f''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin></fillin></cell>
                  <cell halign="right"><m>Q''(0)=</m></cell>
                  <cell><fillin /></cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>
            <p>
              Use your work in <xref ref="T-ez-8a-1-1-updated">Table</xref> to find the formula for <m>Q(x)</m> that satisfies <m>Q(0) = f(0)</m>, <m>Q'(0) = f'(0)</m>, and <m>Q''(0) = f''(0)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Plot <m>f(x)</m>, <m>L(x)</m>, and <m>Q(x)</m> on the same axes, centered at <m>a = 0</m>.  What do you notice?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    
